{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17600430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17600430"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:04:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:04:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15616"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15616"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.89,0.03,0.03,0,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8307"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62061"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8307"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15616"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47507"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2994"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5119"},{"type":"tags","id":"8498"},{"type":"tags","id":"10124"},{"type":"tags","id":"10551"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20047"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20051"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62061"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for investigation of infertility. During the consultation, you explain the hormonal control of male reproduction. You draw a diagram of the hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal axis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best represents the correct sequence of hormonal control?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gonadotropin-releasing hormone \u2192 luteinising hormone \u2192 Leydig cells \u2192 testosterone","Growth hormone-releasing hormone \u2192 insulin-like growth factor-1 \u2192 growth hormone","Corticotropin-releasing hormone \u2192 cortisol \u2192 adrenocorticotropic hormone","Thyroxine and triiodothyronine \u2192 thyroid-stimulating hormone \u2192 thyrotropin-releasing hormone","Gonadotropin-releasing hormone \u2192 luteinising hormone \u2192 Leydig cells \u2192 oestradiol and progesterone"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe hypothalamic-pituitary axis follows a consistent pattern where hypothalamic releasing hormones stimulate the anterior pituitary to release tropic hormones, which then act on target organs to produce end hormones. These end hormones provide negative feedback to both the hypothalamus and pituitary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGonadotropin-releasing hormone \u2192 luteinising hormone \u2192 Leydig cells \u2192 testosterone\u003C/strong\u003E correctly represents the male reproductive axis. GnRH from the hypothalamus stimulates LH release from the anterior pituitary, which acts on Leydig cells in the testes to produce testosterone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrowth hormone-releasing hormone \u2192 insulin-like growth factor-1 \u2192 growth hormone\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The correct sequence is GHRH \u2192 GH \u2192 IGF-1, with GH being released from the anterior pituitary and stimulating IGF-1 production in the liver.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorticotropin-releasing hormone \u2192 cortisol \u2192 adrenocorticotropic hormone\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The correct sequence is CRH \u2192 ACTH \u2192 cortisol, with ACTH being released from the anterior pituitary and acting on the adrenal cortex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroxine and triiodothyronine \u2192 thyroid-stimulating hormone \u2192 thyrotropin-releasing hormone\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The correct sequence is TRH \u2192 TSH \u2192 T3/T4, with TSH being released from the anterior pituitary and acting on the thyroid gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGonadotropin-releasing hormone \u2192 luteinising hormone \u2192 Leydig cells \u2192 oestradiol and progesterone\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as this describes a mixture of male and female reproductive physiology. Leydig cells are found in the testes and produce testosterone, while oestradiol and progesterone are primarily produced by ovarian cells in women.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gonadotropin-releasing hormone stimulates LH release, which acts on Leydig cells to produce testosterone in men.","The hypothalamic-pituitary axis involves releasing hormones from the hypothalamus stimulating the anterior pituitary to release tropic hormones.","Negative feedback loops exist where end hormones inhibit their controlling hormones from the hypothalamus and pituitary."],"references":["Dunlavey CJ. Introduction to the Hypothalamic-Pituitary-Adrenal Axis: Healthy and Dysregulated Stress Responses, Developmental Stress and Neurodegeneration. J Undergrad Neurosci Educ. 2018 Jun 15;16(2):R59-R60. PMID: 30057514; PMCID: PMC6057754.","Smith SM, Vale WW. The role of the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis in neuroendocrine responses to stress. Dialogues Clin Neurosci. 2006;8(4):383-95. doi: 10.31887/DCNS.2006.8.4/ssmith. PMID: 17290797; PMCID: PMC3181830.","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47507"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15616"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47507"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T02:10:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T02:11:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8307"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62061"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"2994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2994"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis","synonyms":["HPA axis"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-09-16T20:19:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":